\begin_layout Subsection
Plantae
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Multicellular organisms with walled eukaryotic cells, which generally have
 vacuoles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
They contain chlorophyll in plastids, responsible for photosynthesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Principal mode of nutrition is photosynthesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Primarily they are non motile, living anchored to a substrate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There is structural differentiation leading towards organs of photosynthesis,
 anchorage and support.
 Even advanced development leads to specialized photosynthetic, vascular
 and covering tissues.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Reproduction is generally, sexual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Animalia
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
They are multicellular organisms.
 They bear eukaryotic cells and lack stiff cell walls.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
They are devoid of plastids and photosynthetic pigments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Nutrition is primarily ingestive and digestion of food occurs in an internal
 cavity called 
\series bold
stomach
\series default
.
 However, some of these organisms show absorptive nutrition, lacking an
 internal cavity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Level of organisation and tissue differentiation is advanced and complex
 than other kingdoms.
 These organisms have evolved neuro-motor and sensory systems and their
 motility is based on contractile fibrils.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
They have developed cells which can contract or transmit impulses.
\end_layout

